<subSubSection id="C344654D632C501C9EF4FE19CBA7FD62" pageId="5" pageNumber="468" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BE136C6632C501C9EF4FE19CBA7FD62" blockId="5.[151,1437,325,677]" pageId="5" pageNumber="468">
<emphasis id="B92AEAD4632C501C9EF4FE19CE6FFE45" bold="true" box="[199,322,397,423]" pageId="5" pageNumber="468">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The male genitalia of this species are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName id="4C5E4D45632C501C9D85FE1BCBEDFE4A" authority="Malicky 1993" authorityName="Malicky" authorityYear="1993" box="[950,1216,398,424]" class="Insecta" family="Polycentropodidae" genus="Polyplectropus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jotham">
<emphasis id="B92AEAD4632C501C9D85FE1BCB33FE4A" box="[950,1054,398,424]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="468">P. jotham</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFCF4B37632C501C9A17FE1ACBEDFE4A" author="Malicky, H." box="[1060,1216,398,424]" pageId="5" pageNumber="468" pagination="1099 - 1136" refId="ref6327" refString="Malicky, H. (1993) Neue asiatische Kocherfliegen (Trichoptera: Philopotamidae Polycentropodidae, Psychomyiidae, Ecnomidae, Hydropsychidae, Leptoceridae). Linzer Biologische Beitrage, 25, 1099 - 1136." type="journal article" year="1993">Malicky 1993</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(also reported from 
<collectingCountry id="F3497656632C501C9EA4FE26CFF2FE2F" box="[151,223,434,461]" name="Nepal" pageId="5" pageNumber="468">Nepal</collectingCountry>
). However, in 
<taxonomicName id="4C5E4D45632C501C9FBAFE27CD27FE2E" authorityName="Malicky" authorityYear="1997" box="[393,522,434,460]" class="Insecta" family="Polycentropodidae" genus="Polyplectropus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="amphion">
<emphasis id="B92AEAD4632C501C9FBAFE27CD27FE2E" box="[393,522,434,460]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="468">P. amphion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the preanal appendages are very broad, leaf-like in lateral view; the spiniform processes of the preanal appendages are strongly directed dorsad in lateral view; and the inferior appendages are broad basally, each with a spine-like, arched process at mid-length on the mesal surface and visible in ventral view. In contrast, in 
<taxonomicName id="4C5E4D45632C501C9F73FD8BCE81FDDA" authorityName="Malicky" authorityYear="1993" box="[320,428,542,568]" class="Insecta" family="Polycentropodidae" genus="Polyplectropus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trichoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="468" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jotham">
<emphasis id="B92AEAD4632C501C9F73FD8BCE81FDDA" box="[320,428,542,568]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="468">P. jotham</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the preanal appendages are not as broad (only finger–like) and narrow in lateral view; the spiniform processes of the preanal appendages are not strongly bent; and the inferior appendages are broad but without any spines or arched processes at mid-length on the mesal surface in ventral view.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
